Many of the safeguards mentioned above are automatic safety systems that are commonly referred to as interlocks. In addition, the refinery has a flare system that will safely burn vented materials from the process units. 
While the emphasis is on prevention of potential hazards, the refinery also implements a number of mitigation measures in the event a release should occur. The SFR recognizes that early detection is an important part of managing a release. An example of a detection safeguard would be that process and storage areas have leak detection systems for hydrocarbons, hydrogen sulfide, and ammonia. In addition, the SFR has perimeter monitors for hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide as well as a fence-line monitoring system. Mitigation is also an important part of managing an accidental release. Examples of mitigation safeguards include emergency block valves, depressurizing, equipment spacing, dikes, curbs and sewers, fire-fighting access, hydrants, monitors, deluge systems, proper fireproofing of vessels, proper pipe supports, and critical instrument controls. 
As part of safeguarding against escalation of an event, the refinery has a comprehensive Emergency Response Program.

